00:53:39.120 --> 00:53:42.460
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you quoted Sunil Khilnani, you know, who said these words in a book review

00:53:42.460 --> 00:53:46.640
[Amit Varma]: of your book on Gandhi, where he said that India was not just battling the empire, Gandhi

00:53:46.640 --> 00:53:49.680
[Amit Varma]: was not just battling the empire, he was also battling India.

00:53:49.680 --> 00:53:54.300
[Amit Varma]: And my question here is, and again, this is something I've tried to explore over multiple

00:53:54.300 --> 00:53:59.840
[Amit Varma]: episodes with multiple people, is that there is a notion that the constitution that we

00:53:59.840 --> 00:54:04.120
[Amit Varma]: got was a liberal constitution, though to my mind, it's not liberal enough, but whatever

00:54:04.120 --> 00:54:08.800
[Amit Varma]: the constitution that we got was a liberal constitution, but imposed upon an illiberal

00:54:08.800 --> 00:54:09.880
[Amit Varma]: society.

00:54:09.880 --> 00:54:12.840
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, can that imposition be liberal at all?

00:54:12.840 --> 00:54:17.400
[Amit Varma]: Taking that thought further, it is held by some now that what has happened today with

00:54:17.400 --> 00:54:22.240
[Amit Varma]: the BJP in power, with Modi in power, is that politics has caught up with society, that

00:54:22.240 --> 00:54:24.880
[Amit Varma]: this is always how our society was.

00:54:24.880 --> 00:54:27.680
[Amit Varma]: So now I have a couple of questions there following up from this.

00:54:27.680 --> 00:54:28.680
[Amit Varma]: Let me answer that.

00:54:28.680 --> 00:54:30.720
[Guest]: It's a very good question.

00:54:30.720 --> 00:54:37.080
[Guest]: It's a very good question, where you say that it was a liberal constitution imposed on a

00:54:37.080 --> 00:54:38.080
[Guest]: illiberal society.

00:54:38.080 --> 00:54:44.320
[Guest]: Now Gandhi recognized this, Gandhi recognized that and Ambedkar and Nehru all recognized,

00:54:44.320 --> 00:54:51.160
[Guest]: which is why they spent the decades leading up to independence, trying to reform society.

00:54:51.160 --> 00:54:54.520
[Guest]: Particularly Gandhi and Ambedkar on the question of caste, Gandhi and Ambedkar on the question

00:54:54.520 --> 00:55:00.040
[Guest]: of caste and Ambedkar and Nehru on the question of gender equality, recognized that this was

00:55:00.040 --> 00:55:01.440
[Guest]: an illiberal society.

00:55:01.440 --> 00:55:09.640
[Guest]: Now, as a historian, I'd like to reemphasize that Gandhi was absolutely alert to this.

00:55:09.640 --> 00:55:14.480
[Guest]: What did Gandhi's early death, premature death read us off?

00:55:14.480 --> 00:55:20.440
[Guest]: Now again, I'd like to give some historical facts that would not be known to your listeners.

00:55:20.440 --> 00:55:28.520
[Guest]: Had Gandhi not been murdered on 30th January 1948, what would he have done in the following

00:55:28.520 --> 00:55:29.680
[Guest]: weeks?

00:55:29.680 --> 00:55:37.280
[Guest]: He was due to go leave for Sevagram on the 2nd of February to have a meeting with constructive

00:55:37.280 --> 00:55:38.280
[Guest]: workers.

00:55:38.280 --> 00:55:45.640
[Guest]: Pushed back one day, 29th January 1948, Gandhi said to casually, he said to some people,

00:55:45.640 --> 00:55:50.920
[Guest]: we must think of disbanding the Congress and making it Lok Sevak committees.

00:55:50.920 --> 00:55:54.040
[Guest]: He didn't mean disband the government.

00:55:54.040 --> 00:55:59.160
[Guest]: He meant that while the government will run, while Nehru and Patel, people like Nehru and

00:55:59.160 --> 00:56:02.840
[Guest]: Patel will be in government, he placed them there, he blessed them as running government.

00:56:02.840 --> 00:56:08.040
[Guest]: We will have a countervailing force in civil society composed of freedom, people from the

00:56:08.040 --> 00:56:14.480
[Guest]: freedom movement who are temperamentally not interested in administration, but in reforming

00:56:14.480 --> 00:56:17.680
[Guest]: on the ground and in liberal society, right?

00:56:17.680 --> 00:56:22.600
[Guest]: So Gandhi's clear understanding was constructive work is as important as politics.

00:56:22.600 --> 00:56:29.600
[Guest]: It goes back to the 1920s and he was going to go to Sevagram on the 2nd of February to

00:56:29.600 --> 00:56:36.160
[Guest]: meet social workers to tell them what could have been done or what should be done to keep

00:56:36.160 --> 00:56:39.360
[Guest]: the government honest, to keep it on its toes, right?

00:56:39.360 --> 00:56:45.120
[Guest]: And if Gandhi had not died, if he'd lived another few years, you would have had a spread

00:56:45.120 --> 00:56:48.120
[Guest]: of the social reform movement within society.

00:56:48.120 --> 00:56:55.840
[Guest]: Gandhi recognized that you can't simply trust the state to reform society.

00:56:55.840 --> 00:57:01.040
[Guest]: You have to have on-ground reforms by activist individuals working non-violently, you know,

00:57:01.040 --> 00:57:02.040
[Guest]: going from Mahalla to Mahalla.

00:57:02.040 --> 00:57:05.760
[Guest]: You just can't have a law saying untouchability is abolished.

00:57:05.760 --> 00:57:10.240
[Guest]: You have to go have people going from Mahalla to Mahalla, village to village saying open

00:57:10.240 --> 00:57:12.200
[Guest]: every well to every person.

00:57:12.200 --> 00:57:15.200
[Guest]: You can't just have a law saying women are equal to men.

00:57:15.200 --> 00:57:20.340
[Guest]: You have to go travel around and to use a later phrase, conscientize ordinary folks

00:57:20.340 --> 00:57:23.060
[Guest]: about the importance of giving women equal rights.

00:57:23.060 --> 00:57:25.360
[Guest]: So Gandhi absolutely recognized this.

00:57:25.360 --> 00:57:33.320
[Guest]: Now among the tragedies of Gandhi's premature death was that Gandhi had not had clearly

00:57:33.320 --> 00:57:35.720
[Guest]: anointed his political successors.

00:57:35.720 --> 00:57:41.760
[Guest]: He had said Nehru and Patel will succeed me politically, but he had not anointed his successors

00:57:41.760 --> 00:57:43.920
[Guest]: in the social work field.

00:57:43.920 --> 00:57:49.240
[Guest]: And through a, I mean, this is maybe a separate discussion, but through pure accident, Gandhi

00:57:49.240 --> 00:57:52.280
[Guest]: died and Vinoba Bhave appointed himself.

00:57:52.280 --> 00:57:56.760
[Guest]: And in my view, he gave that social reform movement a totally wrong direction and a spiritual

00:57:56.760 --> 00:58:01.880
[Guest]: and mystical direction rather than focusing on proper ground level constructive work.

00:58:01.880 --> 00:58:04.160
[Guest]: So I think Gandhi recognized this.

00:58:04.160 --> 00:58:09.160
[Guest]: Gandhi is, again, this is the difference between Gandhi and people like Bose and Bhagat Singh,

00:58:09.160 --> 00:58:15.760
[Guest]: who said political power first and foremost, get rid of the British as early as possible.

00:58:15.760 --> 00:58:19.680
[Guest]: On the other hand, Gandhi said, we must prepare ourselves for independence to go back to what

00:58:19.680 --> 00:58:23.480
[Guest]: Khilani remarks, his battle was against India too.

00:58:23.480 --> 00:58:28.120
[Guest]: And he would have, even after independence, Gandhi would have continued the battle against

00:58:28.120 --> 00:58:30.600
[Guest]: India at the level of everyday life.

00:58:30.600 --> 00:58:31.860
[Amit Varma]: And that's what we missed.

00:58:31.860 --> 00:58:34.640
[Amit Varma]: And here I have to say that, obviously, I agree completely with Gandhi.

00:58:34.640 --> 00:58:38.440
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one of my favorite quotations about politics is by Andrew Breitbart, which is

00:58:38.440 --> 00:58:42.760
[Amit Varma]: quote, politics is downstream of culture, stop quote, which is that, you know, unless

00:58:42.760 --> 00:58:45.320
[Amit Varma]: you change the culture, you cannot change the politics.

00:58:45.320 --> 00:58:46.320
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

00:58:46.320 --> 00:58:51.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, what seems to have happened is that one, the political infrastructure that then was

00:58:51.240 --> 00:58:55.160
[Amit Varma]: shaping the constitution and the country who are today disparagingly termed as liberal

00:58:55.160 --> 00:59:00.560
[Amit Varma]: elites, basically framed a constitution that at that time was out of sync with the culture.

00:59:00.560 --> 00:59:04.680
[Amit Varma]: And what also seems to have happened at that fight, and it wasn't just Gandhi's fight,

00:59:04.680 --> 00:59:09.800
[Amit Varma]: I'm sure a lot of people cared about it, of bringing about a liberal society, essentially,

00:59:09.800 --> 00:59:12.600
[Amit Varma]: some would argue pessimistically that it has failed.

00:59:12.600 --> 00:59:16.760
[Amit Varma]: And because it has failed, today, we have the kind of politics we have.

00:59:16.760 --> 00:59:20.560
[Amit Varma]: And tangentially, the other contestation, like I did an episode with JP Narayan, the

00:59:20.560 --> 00:59:24.960
[Amit Varma]: great political thinker, and his point was that India is not necessarily an illiberal

00:59:24.960 --> 00:59:25.960
[Amit Varma]: society.

00:59:25.960 --> 00:59:30.000
[Amit Varma]: And to some extent, I get where he's coming from, I call it an illiberal society because

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:33.280
[Amit Varma]: of the way women are treated and the lower caste are treated and so on.

00:59:33.280 --> 00:59:38.240
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, our traditions of tolerance and diversity are such that it strikes me

00:59:38.240 --> 00:59:43.040
[Amit Varma]: that it's both and that the so called conservative government in power is actually in one sense

00:59:43.040 --> 00:59:46.560
[Amit Varma]: a radical government, because they're going against our traditions of tolerance.

00:59:46.560 --> 00:59:53.400
[Guest]: I mean, as in, you know, you know, this whole question of Ayodhya, one, one temple, one,

00:59:53.400 --> 00:59:55.440
[Guest]: one holy city for the Hindus and so on.

00:59:55.440 --> 00:59:56.440
[Guest]: Absolutely, absolutely.

00:59:56.440 --> 01:00:01.480
[Amit Varma]: So, so would you say that that Gandhian struggle is finally lost today?

01:00:01.480 --> 01:00:07.640
[Guest]: You know, I would have said it two months ago, I would have not said it's lost, I would

01:00:07.640 --> 01:00:13.240
[Guest]: have what I would have said, Amit, is, and I have said it in print, is to invoke my friend

01:00:13.240 --> 01:00:17.280
[Guest]: Gopal Krishna Gandhi, who is only incidentally a grandson of Gandhi, but essentially a scholar

01:00:17.280 --> 01:00:21.080
[Guest]: and thinker and profound modern interpreter of Gandhi's thought.

01:00:21.080 --> 01:00:26.800
[Guest]: And Gopal Gandhi often used to say to me in private, particularly in the 1990s, the brutal

01:00:26.800 --> 01:00:31.560
[Guest]: decade that saw the demolition of the Babri Masjid and so on, he used to say to me, like

01:00:31.560 --> 01:00:34.640
[Guest]: the Buddha, India will kick out Gandhi.

01:00:34.640 --> 01:00:38.040
[Guest]: And like the Buddha, the rest of the world will affirm Gandhi.

01:00:38.040 --> 01:00:39.440
[Guest]: So I knew that Gandhi would never die.

01:00:39.440 --> 01:00:43.560
[Guest]: I mean, that, you know, there would be people in Eastern Europe, in Latin America, everywhere

01:00:43.560 --> 01:00:47.520
[Guest]: else who would pick up Gandhi and renew his ideas.

01:00:47.520 --> 01:00:52.120
[Guest]: But maybe I was taught by Gopal that Gandhi's influence was steadily diminished within India

01:00:52.120 --> 01:00:56.520
[Guest]: over the last two months, and particularly the protests against DCA.

01:00:56.520 --> 01:01:00.880
[Guest]: Because of these two aspects of Gandhi that they brought, one is Hindu-Muslim harmony,

01:01:00.880 --> 01:01:06.480
[Guest]: and individual civil disobedience, you know, people's power, individual and collective.

01:01:06.480 --> 01:01:10.040
[Amit Varma]: And the photograph of the young girl offering a rose to the policeman was so Gandhian.

01:01:10.040 --> 01:01:11.040
[Guest]: Correct.

01:01:11.040 --> 01:01:15.160
[Guest]: And individual in the sense that it is not organized, contrary to what the BJP says,

01:01:15.160 --> 01:01:17.220
[Guest]: this is totally spontaneous.

01:01:17.220 --> 01:01:24.640
[Guest]: You know, I mean, I said, the day I was detained and came out in an interview, I said that

01:01:24.640 --> 01:01:29.960
[Guest]: in the detention center, there were 400 people, students were overrepresented, and the Congress

01:01:29.960 --> 01:01:33.880
[Guest]: Party was underrepresented, even though, you know, Karnataka is the gutter of the Congress

01:01:33.880 --> 01:01:36.640
[Guest]: Party, but it's pretty strong here as the main opposition party.

01:01:36.640 --> 01:01:40.680
[Guest]: So I think these two aspects of Gandhi have come back in India through this, the current

01:01:40.680 --> 01:01:47.360
[Guest]: wave of protests, you know, spirited coming out in the streets, non-violently.

01:01:47.360 --> 01:01:52.080
[Guest]: And you know, this whole, I mean, that great, the slogan, I don't know who coined it in

01:01:52.080 --> 01:01:53.080
[Guest]: Bombay.

01:01:53.080 --> 01:01:56.080
[Guest]: Jab Hindu-Muslim razi, kya karega nazi?

01:01:56.080 --> 01:01:57.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:01:57.080 --> 01:02:01.080
[Amit Varma]: The name escapes me, actually, you know, somebody put this up on his Instagram, and then it

01:02:01.080 --> 01:02:02.080
[Guest]: got onto a t-shirt.

01:02:02.080 --> 01:02:03.080
[Guest]: Okay.

01:02:03.080 --> 01:02:04.520
[Guest]: Jab Hindu-Muslim razi, kya karega nazi?

01:02:04.520 --> 01:02:07.440
[Guest]: Now, it's that kind of sharp satire.

01:02:07.440 --> 01:02:12.840
[Guest]: The phrasing is not Gandhian, but the sentiment is totally Gandhian, the phrasing is too satirical

01:02:12.840 --> 01:02:15.000
[Guest]: and sharp to be Gandhian, right?

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:26.040
[Guest]: So this aspect, you know, I mean, Hindu-Muslim-Sikh-Isai razi, you know, I mean, the whole Rangarhad

01:02:26.040 --> 01:02:28.240
[Guest]: in Shaheen Bagh by Sardars, you know, that's fabulous.

01:02:28.240 --> 01:02:30.280
[Guest]: I mean, that's like, that's just wonderful, right?

01:02:30.280 --> 01:02:33.120
[Guest]: So I'm hopeful that Gandhi has not been forgotten in his homeland.

01:02:33.120 --> 01:02:37.040
[Guest]: I mean, two months ago, I would have thought that it's elsewhere that people are, you know,

01:02:37.040 --> 01:02:38.040
[Guest]: truly remembering him.

01:02:38.040 --> 01:02:41.920
[Guest]: I mean, the Prime Minister quotes him totally cynically and instrumentally.

01:02:41.920 --> 01:02:46.600
[Guest]: I mean, the Prime Minister can write an article on October 2nd in the New York Times, and

01:02:46.600 --> 01:02:49.560
[Guest]: not mention Hindu-Muslim harmony, which is what Gandhi lived and died for.

01:02:49.560 --> 01:02:53.960
[Guest]: You can mention Einstein praised him, Mandela praised him, all kinds of stuff, right?

01:02:53.960 --> 01:03:00.640
[Guest]: So but I think ordinary people, and admirably, not only Gandhi, but also Ambedkar, also Bhagat

01:03:00.640 --> 01:03:01.640
[Amit Varma]: Singh.

01:03:01.640 --> 01:03:02.640
[Amit Varma]: That's great.

01:03:02.640 --> 01:03:03.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:03:03.640 --> 01:03:08.160
[Amit Varma]: And I wrote a piece on this, where I was sort of looking at politics through the lens of

01:03:08.160 --> 01:03:12.080
[Amit Varma]: economics and trying to examine why is it that during our freedom struggle, we had so

01:03:12.080 --> 01:03:16.560
[Amit Varma]: many great leaders, and people often bemoan that we don't have leaders like that anymore.

01:03:16.560 --> 01:03:20.680
[Amit Varma]: And to me, the economic answer boiled down to incentives, that at that point in time,

01:03:20.680 --> 01:03:24.000
[Amit Varma]: all the leaders that we had, they weren't motivated by the lust for power, because it

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:29.120
[Amit Varma]: was no power to we had, they were motivated by abstract ideals, and that idealism to them

01:03:29.120 --> 01:03:30.120
[Amit Varma]: there.

01:03:30.120 --> 01:03:32.480
[Amit Varma]: And it was that kind of person who got attracted.

01:03:32.480 --> 01:03:36.520
[Amit Varma]: And in the modern Indian state, where the state is such a rent-seeking predatory behemoth,

01:03:36.520 --> 01:03:41.400
[Amit Varma]: it attracts the kind of people who will lust for power and who will go on.

01:03:41.400 --> 01:03:47.840
[Amit Varma]: Now, what has given me hope in the last couple of months, as you said, is that that kind

01:03:47.840 --> 01:03:52.640
[Amit Varma]: of spirit, that kind of idealism seems to be reappearing in the public spaces right

01:03:52.640 --> 01:03:57.160
[Amit Varma]: now, but is not yet there in politics, but is reappearing in public spaces and maybe

01:03:57.160 --> 01:04:00.280
[Amit Varma]: out of the crucible of this future politicians will emerge.

01:04:00.280 --> 01:04:03.560
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, I sort of look at the political marketplace.

01:04:03.560 --> 01:04:05.360
[Amit Varma]: And we'll talk about the BGP in the Congress.

01:04:05.360 --> 01:04:10.600
[Amit Varma]: But the example that kind of struck me was that in Delhi, the Aam Aadmi Party made the

01:04:10.600 --> 01:04:15.160
[Amit Varma]: perhaps practical, perhaps cynical decision to not fight this battle for principles just

01:04:15.160 --> 01:04:20.160
[Amit Varma]: because they are running an election on governance very soon, extremely soon, and therefore not

01:04:20.160 --> 01:04:21.840
[Amit Varma]: to get involved in all of this.

01:04:21.840 --> 01:04:25.800
[Amit Varma]: But what they have done because of this is that they didn't speak out against 370.

01:04:25.800 --> 01:04:28.120
[Amit Varma]: In fact, they supported the abolition of 370.

01:04:28.120 --> 01:04:30.280
[Amit Varma]: They have completely ignored this issue.

01:04:30.280 --> 01:04:34.460
[Amit Varma]: So what is therefore happening is that in the political space, there is no one speaking

01:04:34.460 --> 01:04:40.480
[Amit Varma]: of for these principles anymore, because the incentives of oh, I have to win the next election

01:04:40.480 --> 01:04:41.600
[Amit Varma]: is coming into play.

01:04:41.600 --> 01:04:42.800
[Amit Varma]: And they're behaving rationally.

01:04:42.800 --> 01:04:44.400
[Amit Varma]: We can't judge them for this.

01:04:44.400 --> 01:04:45.800
[Amit Varma]: But how do we get past this?

01:04:45.800 --> 01:04:47.360
[Guest]: You know, it's hard to say.

01:04:47.360 --> 01:04:50.560
[Guest]: I mean, it's very, very hard to see how societies transform themselves.

01:04:50.560 --> 01:04:55.960
[Guest]: And I mean, the last time we had a movement of this kind, you know, the India against

01:04:55.960 --> 01:05:00.720
[Guest]: corruption, it gave birth to the cult of Kedriwal, who, you know, threw everyone else out of

01:05:00.720 --> 01:05:02.840
[Guest]: his movement and his party, right.

01:05:02.840 --> 01:05:07.040
[Guest]: But I think there's, I think, because there's so many young people and across India, it's

01:05:07.040 --> 01:05:10.480
[Guest]: not just Delhi, I mean, the media is focused on Delhi, because the media is in Delhi and

01:05:10.480 --> 01:05:13.160
[Guest]: Shaheen Bagh is in Delhi and Jamia is in Delhi.

01:05:13.160 --> 01:05:18.520
[Guest]: But all over, you know, if you see the scenes from Bihar, today, there's something from

01:05:18.520 --> 01:05:22.160
[Guest]: Nagaland, Kerala, Kerala, Kerala, of course, Kerala, of course.

01:05:22.160 --> 01:05:27.520
[Guest]: But many in Bombay, I mean, I think the BJP's hubris in not striking a deal with the Shiv Sena

01:05:27.520 --> 01:05:31.680
[Guest]: has been good for Indian democracy, whatever else, you know, and Indian pluralism.

01:05:31.680 --> 01:05:39.840
[Guest]: I mean, it's made, you know, just as an aside, Eric Hobsbawm, in his memoir, in Interesting

01:05:39.840 --> 01:05:48.280
[Guest]: Times, has a kind of a throwaway line where he says, there are many ex-communists.

01:05:48.280 --> 01:05:50.480
[Guest]: But have you ever met an ex-fascist?

01:05:50.480 --> 01:05:53.560
[Guest]: All right, now, I thought that's quite a profound line.

01:05:53.560 --> 01:05:56.360
[Guest]: But I think in Maharashtra now, there are quite a few ex-fascists, I mean, if you look

01:05:56.360 --> 01:06:03.040
[Guest]: at what the Shiv Sena is talking about now, which is great, I mean, if the Shiv Sena has

01:06:03.040 --> 01:06:07.240
[Guest]: abandoned his hardline Hindutva, you know, much more hardline even than the BJP, right?

01:06:07.240 --> 01:06:11.520
[Guest]: And now, I was told, I don't know that the preamble is going to be read out in every

01:06:11.520 --> 01:06:13.280
[Guest]: school in Maharashtra, right?

01:06:13.280 --> 01:06:20.600
[Guest]: So I think these things are happening, and whether they translate into diminished returns

01:06:20.600 --> 01:06:25.200
[Guest]: for the BJP, in the ballot box, whether they translate into true pluralism and tolerance

01:06:25.200 --> 01:06:26.720
[Guest]: and governance, we don't know.

01:06:26.720 --> 01:06:30.600
[Guest]: But the last two or three months have been the most hopeful in India for a decade.

01:06:30.600 --> 01:06:37.800
[Guest]: Well before, I mean, I think from 2010-11, Manmohan Singh lost the plot, you know, in

01:06:37.800 --> 01:06:38.880
[Guest]: many different ways.

01:06:38.880 --> 01:06:44.520
[Guest]: And I'm not one who is nostalgic for Manmohan Singh's regime, his first term was okay, second

01:06:44.520 --> 01:06:45.800
[Guest]: term was disastrous.

01:06:45.800 --> 01:06:50.440
[Guest]: He demeaned the office of the Prime Minister in many, many ways, including in his utterly

01:06:50.440 --> 01:06:53.960
[Guest]: shameful comment that I'd be honored to serve under Rahul Gandhi.

01:06:53.960 --> 01:06:57.240
[Guest]: He prepared the way for Narendra Modi comments of that kind.

01:06:57.240 --> 01:07:02.800
[Guest]: So I'm the most hopeful I've been in a decade, I'd say.

01:07:02.800 --> 01:07:06.400
[Amit Varma]: And let's kind of talk about the BJP, because it's very interesting that again, it might

01:07:06.400 --> 01:07:10.600
[Amit Varma]: seem from this vantage point, that it was inevitable that it would end up here with

01:07:10.600 --> 01:07:13.000
[Amit Varma]: Modi and Shah doing the things that they are doing.

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:16.680
[Amit Varma]: But it wasn't inevitable long ago, you once had a Prime Minister in Vajpayee, who many

01:07:16.680 --> 01:07:20.880
[Amit Varma]: regard as one of the best we have had, a far more cultured man than the people in charge

01:07:20.880 --> 01:07:21.880
[Amit Varma]: today.

01:07:21.880 --> 01:07:26.840
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, what does the evolution of the BJP tell you, and also, there is a dichotomy

01:07:26.840 --> 01:07:32.080
[Amit Varma]: here that on the one hand, the BJP is a one party driven by ideology, which is the ideology

01:07:32.080 --> 01:07:36.680
[Amit Varma]: of the Sindhu Rashtra, and blah, blah, blah, which comes from its parent, the RSS.

01:07:36.680 --> 01:07:41.000
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, they are brought to power and are expanding by the will to power,

01:07:41.000 --> 01:07:46.240
[Amit Varma]: yes, where they are doing mergers and acquisitions and expanding vote base and all of that.

01:07:46.240 --> 01:07:50.500
[Amit Varma]: And you know, so what gives are they at some point going to become an efficient vote gathering

01:07:50.500 --> 01:07:55.480
[Amit Varma]: machine much like the Congress once was and ideology doesn't matter, or is this ideology

01:07:55.480 --> 01:07:59.280
[Amit Varma]: actually going to play out in the ways that in the last year, it seems certainly it's

01:07:59.280 --> 01:08:00.280
[Amit Varma]: accelerated?

01:08:00.280 --> 01:08:03.960
[Guest]: No, I think the ideology is has accelerated.

01:08:03.960 --> 01:08:08.280
[Guest]: There's no question about it has become more strongly ideological in his second term.

01:08:08.280 --> 01:08:15.000
[Guest]: And he's done things that I mean, I'm in some ways, because it's shown its naked ugly face,

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:18.760
[Guest]: you've had the pushback because they thought that with Kashmir and Ayodhya was not enough,

01:08:18.760 --> 01:08:22.280
[Guest]: we should also have this third, you know, radical move.

01:08:22.280 --> 01:08:25.760
[Guest]: But I think the way the BJP has transformed, and I'm not the first to say this, I mean,

01:08:25.760 --> 01:08:30.320
[Guest]: people like Suhashpal Sikar and others said it before, is that it's become a high command

01:08:30.320 --> 01:08:31.440
[Guest]: party, which it never was.

01:08:31.440 --> 01:08:35.960
[Guest]: I mean, it's sort of mimicked what Indira Gandhi and Sanjay Gandhi did to the Congress

01:08:35.960 --> 01:08:43.480
[Guest]: in the 70s, that they converted a decentralized, diverse party with many vigorous state units,

01:08:43.480 --> 01:08:47.280
[Guest]: district units, important state leaders into this high command party.

01:08:47.280 --> 01:08:51.320
[Guest]: I mean, in that column, I mentioned that I wrote about Modi not trusting advisors.

01:08:51.320 --> 01:08:55.760
[Guest]: I mean, why didn't he take Shivraj Singh Chavan and Rahman Singh into this cabinet, right?

01:08:55.760 --> 01:08:57.680
[Guest]: Because they have to push everyone down.

01:08:57.680 --> 01:09:01.960
[Guest]: Modi and Shah have to control everything in the way in which Indira Gandhi and Sanjay

01:09:01.960 --> 01:09:04.360
[Guest]: Gandhi did and later Sonia Gandhi and Ahmed Patel did.

01:09:04.360 --> 01:09:06.560
[Guest]: I mean, Sonia Gandhi and Ahmed Patel are the same.

01:09:06.560 --> 01:09:10.360
[Guest]: And even now, if the Congress wants to revive itself, it has to rid itself of that culture.

01:09:10.360 --> 01:09:14.040
[Guest]: I mean, it has to give people like Amrindar Singh and Sindhara Maiya and Bhupesh Bagel

01:09:14.040 --> 01:09:19.160
[Guest]: much more space than Mr. Ahmed Patel and Mrs. Sonia Gandhi are willing to give them, right?

01:09:19.160 --> 01:09:23.200
[Guest]: So this transformational BJP, right, that it's not a grassroots party, it has become

01:09:23.200 --> 01:09:25.200
[Guest]: a high command party.

01:09:25.200 --> 01:09:30.080
[Guest]: And you know, this may of course, it's already had some diminishing returns.

01:09:30.080 --> 01:09:33.640
[Guest]: You know, one very interesting, I mean, these are things that have to be empirically studied.

01:09:33.640 --> 01:09:36.800
[Guest]: It's also become a cult of personality party, which it never was before.

01:09:36.800 --> 01:09:39.800
[Guest]: It was always against Vyakti Pooja, right?

01:09:39.800 --> 01:09:43.280
[Guest]: Even in Vajpayee's time, there was a three murti, Vajpayee, Advani, Joshi, right?

01:09:43.280 --> 01:09:47.040
[Guest]: It was always against Vyakti Pooja and now it's a cult of personality.

01:09:47.040 --> 01:09:52.800
[Guest]: It's a cult of personality promoted by the Prime Minister and endorsed by second in command.

01:09:52.800 --> 01:09:56.880
[Guest]: Who thinks, rightly or wrongly, that Modi's name wins elections.

01:09:56.880 --> 01:10:01.480
[Guest]: So he has also abandoned this RSS's belief in collective leadership and it's all cult

01:10:01.480 --> 01:10:02.480
[Guest]: of personality.

01:10:02.480 --> 01:10:07.120
[Guest]: Now, this has had diminishing returns in the sense that in Jharkhand, for example, the

01:10:07.120 --> 01:10:12.200
[Guest]: argument was that when social reform was done by the Manmohan Singh regime, so Mandrega

01:10:12.200 --> 01:10:18.920
[Guest]: was Dharmanand, if Raman Singh implemented Mandrega well, he would get some credit.

01:10:18.920 --> 01:10:23.520
[Guest]: But now if Raghubir Das implements, you know, Swachh Bharat well, he'll get no credit because

01:10:23.520 --> 01:10:25.440
[Guest]: it's only Modi's photograph everywhere, you know.

01:10:25.440 --> 01:10:26.440
[Guest]: So, right.

01:10:26.440 --> 01:10:32.160
[Guest]: So, this is the kind of the khaikabad culture and the cult of the personality are transforming

01:10:32.160 --> 01:10:36.920
[Guest]: the BJP in ways in which actually may be sowing the seeds of his long term decline.

01:10:36.920 --> 01:10:37.920
[Guest]: That's the hopeful part.

01:10:37.920 --> 01:10:45.200
[Guest]: You know, obviously, the not so hopeful part is that while adopting a high command culture,

01:10:45.200 --> 01:10:50.960
[Guest]: while promoting and embellishing a cult of personality, it is not abandoned, but rather

01:10:50.960 --> 01:10:56.600
[Guest]: consolidated its hardcore sectarian ideological bigoted beliefs against minorities.

01:10:56.600 --> 01:10:58.080
[Guest]: And that's the dangerous part.

01:10:58.080 --> 01:11:01.840
[Guest]: But electorally, I think they may have still win state elections, they may win by a grand

01:11:01.840 --> 01:11:03.960
[Guest]: start in four years and so on and so forth.

01:11:03.960 --> 01:11:09.080
[Guest]: But I think once you undermine state units in the way that they're doing, and local leadership,

01:11:09.080 --> 01:11:12.920
[Guest]: you know, you, you catapult people from the top that you know, in Haryana, even the election

01:11:12.920 --> 01:11:16.880
[Guest]: Amit Shah will decide, Maharashtra, even Amit Shah will decide, it won't be the local legislature.

01:11:16.880 --> 01:11:20.400
[Guest]: That's what Indira Gandhi and Sonia Gandhi used to do and see what happened to the Congress

01:11:20.400 --> 01:11:21.400
[Amit Varma]: Party.

01:11:21.400 --> 01:11:25.160
[Amit Varma]: In fact, when I was a child, I remember seeing this very striking image of a group of of

01:11:25.160 --> 01:11:30.480
[Amit Varma]: a chronology, chronology, Samjhi, of a chronology of mafia dons, from one to another.

01:11:30.480 --> 01:11:34.600
[Amit Varma]: And the first guy was five foot six, and everyone who succeeded him, which was basically a second

01:11:34.600 --> 01:11:38.000
[Amit Varma]: in command taking charge after he died, or whatever was shorter than him, till you got

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:42.840
[Amit Varma]: to a guy at the end, who was four foot nine, which kind of seems to speak to the tendency

01:11:42.840 --> 01:11:48.800
[Amit Varma]: of some leaders to always appoint people next to them who cannot threaten them.

01:11:48.800 --> 01:11:49.800
[Amit Varma]: That's it.

01:11:49.800 --> 01:11:51.960
[Guest]: And, and, and which is why you have these different parties.

01:11:51.960 --> 01:11:56.240
[Guest]: I mean, what Modi should really have done, Shivraj Singh Chavan, Raman Singh and Vasundhara

01:11:56.240 --> 01:12:00.520
[Guest]: Jain to the cabinet, and they would completely have differed him, they did they don't want

01:12:00.520 --> 01:12:03.720
[Guest]: his job, you know, he's the Supreme Leader, but there are three competent and experienced

01:12:03.720 --> 01:12:04.720
[Guest]: administrators, right?

01:12:04.720 --> 01:12:06.720
[Guest]: Surely you want them in your team.

01:12:06.720 --> 01:12:12.480
[Guest]: Are you so insecure that you must only have your Rajya Sabha MPs like Nirmala Sitharaman

01:12:12.480 --> 01:12:15.760
[Guest]: and Jai Shankar and others to just, you know, who are toadies to you?

01:12:15.760 --> 01:12:17.640
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this is mystifying.

01:12:17.640 --> 01:12:21.200
[Amit Varma]: The other tendency which people have pointed out about the BJP is that each leader seems

01:12:21.200 --> 01:12:26.240
[Amit Varma]: to make the leader before him seem moderate, like Vajpayee to Shama Prasad and Advani to

01:12:26.240 --> 01:12:29.040
[Amit Varma]: Vajpayee and Modi to Advani and maybe Amit Shah.

01:12:29.040 --> 01:12:32.120
[Guest]: No, I don't think Vajpayee was less moderate than Shama Prasad.

01:12:32.120 --> 01:12:33.120
[Guest]: You didn't?

01:12:33.120 --> 01:12:34.120
[Guest]: Not at all.

01:12:34.120 --> 01:12:35.120
[Guest]: Not at all.

01:12:35.120 --> 01:12:36.120
[Guest]: Shama Prasad was essentially...

01:12:36.120 --> 01:12:40.920
[Guest]: No, no, no, no, no, no, I don't think so, I don't think so, but certainly, Advani, Vajpayee

01:12:40.920 --> 01:12:47.400
[Guest]: made Advani seem moderate, and you know, Advani made Vajpayee seem moderate and Modi makes

01:12:47.400 --> 01:12:48.400
[Guest]: Advani seem moderate.

01:12:48.400 --> 01:12:58.120
[Amit Varma]: Is there a logic to this procession that each successor then has to become more strident

01:12:58.120 --> 01:12:59.120
[Guest]: to appeal to the base or something?

01:12:59.120 --> 01:13:05.000
[Guest]: You know, there's one aspect of what's going on in our country today, which I think insufficient

01:13:05.000 --> 01:13:09.240
[Guest]: attention has been paid, is the regional diversity.

01:13:09.240 --> 01:13:13.920
[Guest]: Modi is an all India leader, but Adityanath cannot become an all India leader, not because

01:13:13.920 --> 01:13:20.720
[Guest]: he doesn't have charisma, but his charisma is of a kind that will appeal in UP and Bihar

01:13:20.720 --> 01:13:26.560
[Guest]: and not in Maharashtra and in Karnataka and in Kerala, but this is something that Modi

01:13:26.560 --> 01:13:34.000
[Guest]: shared only with Indira Gandhi and Nehru, that his charisma, you know, went across state

01:13:34.000 --> 01:13:39.800
[Guest]: boundaries for whatever reason, you know, you felt this guy is for all of India, maybe

01:13:39.800 --> 01:13:44.960
[Guest]: not for the Muslims, but for Hindus everywhere, at least, right, but Adityanath went to Kerala

01:13:44.960 --> 01:13:48.920
[Guest]: to lead a march and had to return within one day.

01:13:48.920 --> 01:13:53.360
[Guest]: So I think it'd be interesting to see, he clearly is positioning himself as some kind

01:13:53.360 --> 01:13:56.920
[Guest]: of successor in the short to medium term, I mean, if you look at it, what he's been

01:13:56.920 --> 01:13:58.680
[Guest]: doing in UP.

01:13:58.680 --> 01:14:03.320
[Guest]: But I think this kind of pan Indian appeal that Modi has, which even Vajpayee didn't

01:14:03.320 --> 01:14:08.400
[Guest]: have in the same way, you know, Vajpayee was a great coalition builder, a great team builder,

01:14:08.400 --> 01:14:15.560
[Guest]: but he didn't have that kind of vote gathering ability that Modi had, even still today has,

01:14:15.560 --> 01:14:17.520
[Amit Varma]: and only Nehru and Indira had it.

01:14:17.520 --> 01:14:18.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:14:18.520 --> 01:14:22.080
[Amit Varma]: And now we inevitably also have to turn our attention to the Congress.

01:14:22.080 --> 01:14:26.280
[Amit Varma]: And you know, my sentiment of the Congress is this way I see the nation today, the our

01:14:26.280 --> 01:14:29.280
[Amit Varma]: big problem is that Modi is in power.

01:14:29.280 --> 01:14:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Part of the reason for that is that there is a terribly weak opposition.

01:14:33.000 --> 01:14:36.440
[Amit Varma]: Part of the reason for that terribly weak opposition is that our largest opposition

01:14:36.440 --> 01:14:41.920
[Amit Varma]: party, the only other national party has been crippled by the feudalism within the party.

01:14:41.920 --> 01:14:44.840
[Amit Varma]: So if you oppose Modi, you have to oppose that feudalism.

01:14:44.840 --> 01:14:49.840
[Amit Varma]: You have to therefore oppose the family and you've got a lot of flag for it recently.

01:14:49.840 --> 01:14:53.320
[Amit Varma]: And I absolutely felt for you and I share your views on this.

01:14:53.320 --> 01:14:57.840
[Amit Varma]: But and to me, what I tell my friends is whatever anger you might have against the family for

01:14:57.840 --> 01:15:01.680
[Amit Varma]: all the harm they've done through the decades, the point is, and this is something that I'm

01:15:01.680 --> 01:15:06.200
[Amit Varma]: sure you'd feel viscerally that the Congress was once a vessel for really great leaders.

01:15:06.200 --> 01:15:08.920
[Amit Varma]: And that organizational infrastructure still exists.

01:15:08.920 --> 01:15:13.720
[Amit Varma]: So if only the spaces are for new leaders to come up, that's where the hope lies.

01:15:13.720 --> 01:15:16.080
[Guest]: No, they still are some good leaders in the Congress.

01:15:16.080 --> 01:15:19.880
[Guest]: And they're not the normal leaders whom Delhi people talk about.

01:15:19.880 --> 01:15:21.880
[Guest]: They're not Sindhiya and Pilot.

01:15:21.880 --> 01:15:27.000
[Guest]: They're not Sindhiya and Pilot or Shashi Tharoor, no, no, no.

01:15:27.000 --> 01:15:33.680
[Guest]: As far as I can see, there are three leaders of the Congress who are, I think, are actually

01:15:33.680 --> 01:15:35.800
[Guest]: mass leaders.

01:15:35.800 --> 01:15:39.720
[Guest]: One is Amarinder Singh, the other is Siddharam Iyer of my state.

01:15:39.720 --> 01:15:42.920
[Guest]: And the third is the most interesting because he's the youngest and he's from a Hindi-speaking

01:15:42.920 --> 01:15:49.080
[Guest]: state is Bhupesh Bagel of Chhattisgarh, who in a year in power has actually grown enormously.

01:15:49.080 --> 01:15:52.400
[Guest]: And it'll be interesting to see whether the high command and the family sees him as a

01:15:52.400 --> 01:15:54.840
[Guest]: threat, which they very well might already.

01:15:54.840 --> 01:15:59.040
[Guest]: But he's so I think not Kamal Nath, none of these people, but I think Amarinder and Siddharam

01:15:59.040 --> 01:16:01.400
[Guest]: Iyer are strongly rooted in their state.

01:16:01.400 --> 01:16:04.560
[Guest]: You know, they have stoked regional pride in a very strong way.

01:16:04.560 --> 01:16:09.600
[Guest]: They're seen as tough, authoritative and with a mass connect, right.

01:16:09.600 --> 01:16:11.360
[Guest]: And Bhupesh Bagel is a very interesting character.

01:16:11.360 --> 01:16:16.120
[Guest]: And if Sonia Gandhi was wise, she would make him the next Congress president, someone like

01:16:16.120 --> 01:16:19.560
[Guest]: him the next Congress president, because that's the only way you can take on Modi.

01:16:19.560 --> 01:16:23.360
[Guest]: You know, several things have changed, you know, in the popular perception of the Congress

01:16:23.360 --> 01:16:24.440
[Guest]: Party.

01:16:24.440 --> 01:16:30.400
[Guest]: One is, you know, Sonia Gandhi 20 years ago, many ordinary Indians were sympathetic towards

01:16:30.400 --> 01:16:31.400
[Guest]: her.

01:16:31.400 --> 01:16:37.120
[Guest]: They said, here is someone who's known to horrible bereavements, you know, the brutal

01:16:37.120 --> 01:16:41.400
[Guest]: murder of her adored husband and her revered mother-in-law.

01:16:41.400 --> 01:16:43.740
[Guest]: And yet she's come to serve us.

01:16:43.740 --> 01:16:46.480
[Guest]: She was hardworking, unlike her son.

01:16:46.480 --> 01:16:49.680
[Guest]: She had political acumen, unlike her son.

01:16:49.680 --> 01:16:52.000
[Guest]: But today, she's seen in a different light.

01:16:52.000 --> 01:16:59.400
[Guest]: 20 years later, she's not seen as the courageous, sacrificing person, but as someone who simply

01:16:59.400 --> 01:17:00.960
[Guest]: wants to promote her son.

01:17:00.960 --> 01:17:01.960
[Guest]: That's how she's seen.

01:17:01.960 --> 01:17:02.960
[Guest]: Right.

01:17:02.960 --> 01:17:05.080
[Guest]: So even Sonia Gandhi is bad news electorally.

01:17:05.080 --> 01:17:09.240
[Guest]: She may be better news for the Congress Party than her son, because she's a more adroit

01:17:09.240 --> 01:17:13.040
[Guest]: tactician and because coalition partners trust her.

01:17:13.040 --> 01:17:16.720
[Guest]: You know, Sharad Pawar will go and meet Sonia Gandhi, he will not go and meet Rahul Gandhi.

01:17:16.720 --> 01:17:17.720
[Guest]: Right.

01:17:17.720 --> 01:17:20.460
[Guest]: To that limited extent, she has done some damage control.

01:17:20.460 --> 01:17:22.400
[Guest]: But she cannot be the future of the Congress Party.

01:17:22.400 --> 01:17:26.480
[Guest]: The family cannot be the future of the Congress Party, if the Congress Party wants to mount

01:17:26.480 --> 01:17:29.480
[Guest]: an effective opposition to the BJP.

01:17:29.480 --> 01:17:33.000
[Guest]: And I think that's something which I have said many times before.

01:17:33.000 --> 01:17:37.080
[Guest]: It so happened that when I said it in Kerala, it got much more flack than ever before, because

01:17:37.080 --> 01:17:40.480
[Guest]: I think partly because people felt this is not the time to say it.

01:17:40.480 --> 01:17:45.080
[Guest]: When there's an all India movement against this nasty regime, and of course, I yield

01:17:45.080 --> 01:17:48.400
[Guest]: to no one in saying it's a nasty regime, why is he diverting attention by talking about

01:17:48.400 --> 01:17:49.400
[Guest]: leadership?

01:17:49.400 --> 01:17:50.400
[Guest]: Right.

01:17:50.400 --> 01:17:51.400
[Guest]: That's why it got so much flack.

01:17:51.400 --> 01:17:57.300
[Guest]: I think the closer we come to 2024, this question will have to be posed more and more insistently.

01:17:57.300 --> 01:18:02.160
[Guest]: That elections, national elections today, are about ideology, we can fight Hindutva

01:18:02.160 --> 01:18:06.520
[Guest]: ideologically, they're about organization and coordination, the opposition needs better

01:18:06.520 --> 01:18:08.400
[Guest]: organization and coordination.

01:18:08.400 --> 01:18:12.840
[Guest]: But they're also increasingly presidential and hence about personalities, right?

01:18:12.840 --> 01:18:16.640
[Guest]: So I think that's a question that will come.

01:18:16.640 --> 01:18:17.640
[Guest]: And we'll see how it unfolds.

01:18:17.640 --> 01:18:21.480
[Amit Varma]: There's also a question of deeper party cultures, like I remember watching this interview of

01:18:21.480 --> 01:18:24.720
[Amit Varma]: Mahua Maitra a while ago, and whatever one thinks of her, she's a young leader who's

01:18:24.720 --> 01:18:25.720
[Amit Varma]: captured the imagination.

01:18:25.720 --> 01:18:26.720
[Amit Varma]: Correct.

01:18:26.720 --> 01:18:29.600
[Amit Varma]: And I remember Mahua Maitra said that she was once part of the Congress 10 years ago,

01:18:29.600 --> 01:18:34.880
[Amit Varma]: but she left because she felt there was an ingrained sexism, and that people were condescending

01:18:34.880 --> 01:18:37.760
[Amit Varma]: towards her and were not letting it come up.

01:18:37.760 --> 01:18:39.560
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, she had to make a space somewhere.

01:18:39.560 --> 01:18:43.640
[Amit Varma]: And my argument always has been that if the Congress can just, you know, get past that

01:18:43.640 --> 01:18:47.920
[Amit Varma]: feudal culture and make space for new leaders, you know, nature abhors a vacuum.

01:18:47.920 --> 01:18:48.920
[Amit Varma]: My other sort of...

01:18:48.920 --> 01:18:49.920
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

01:18:49.920 --> 01:18:50.920
[Amit Varma]: I completely agree with you.

01:18:50.920 --> 01:18:51.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:18:51.920 --> 01:18:55.840
[Amit Varma]: And my other sort of follow up question is that, like on the one hand, of course, you

01:18:55.840 --> 01:18:58.720
[Amit Varma]: know, just to go back to the criticism that you received for a moment, I thought what

01:18:58.720 --> 01:19:02.960
[Amit Varma]: a lot of people were doing were creating these false binaries, where on the one hand, there's

01:19:02.960 --> 01:19:05.160
[Amit Varma]: Modi, on the other hand, there's the opposition, including Rahul.

01:19:05.160 --> 01:19:07.160
[Amit Varma]: And if you're criticizing Rahul, you're somehow helping Modi.

01:19:07.160 --> 01:19:09.040
[Amit Varma]: And I think absolutely the opposite is true.

01:19:09.040 --> 01:19:11.040
[Amit Varma]: They're both part of the problem.

01:19:11.040 --> 01:19:14.800
[Amit Varma]: My other question here is that if we look at Indian political parties, and I always

01:19:14.800 --> 01:19:18.920
[Amit Varma]: say that we can't look at Indian politics through the standard prism of left and right.

01:19:18.920 --> 01:19:22.840
[Amit Varma]: And that's, you know, we are mimicking the West in that frame of thinking, but that frame

01:19:22.840 --> 01:19:23.960
[Amit Varma]: is not relevant.

01:19:23.960 --> 01:19:27.800
[Amit Varma]: And the reason is that if you apply that frame, you will find that every Indian party in its

01:19:27.800 --> 01:19:32.760
[Amit Varma]: economics is left of center in the sense it is statist, and in its approach to society

01:19:32.760 --> 01:19:37.560
[Amit Varma]: and culture is right of center in terms of denying freedoms and, you know, the things

01:19:37.560 --> 01:19:42.520
[Amit Varma]: that Kamal Nath has done as the CM of MP is the cow protection and all of that.

01:19:42.520 --> 01:19:45.120
[Amit Varma]: This then points to a fundamental problem in the culture itself, right?

01:19:45.120 --> 01:19:46.920
[Amit Varma]: So where is our hope going to come from?

01:19:46.920 --> 01:19:48.280
[Guest]: Well, that's very true.

01:19:48.280 --> 01:19:54.760
[Guest]: I broadly absolutely right that when it comes to, you know, economics, leftist or statist

01:19:54.760 --> 01:19:59.360
[Guest]: more statist, at best welfarist, most often statist, yeah.

01:19:59.360 --> 01:20:03.400
[Guest]: And with a few favorite 20 capitalists are there an open market for everyone.

01:20:03.400 --> 01:20:06.400
[Guest]: And when it comes to, you know, culture and freedoms, they are authoritarian.

01:20:06.400 --> 01:20:11.840
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, this is partly, you know, I don't know, it's partly our diversity, our

01:20:11.840 --> 01:20:16.680
[Guest]: size, our poverty, our feudal heritage, so change will be slow and incremental.

01:20:16.680 --> 01:20:22.160
[Guest]: But I think young people, things are changing, for example, one way in which India and that's

01:20:22.160 --> 01:20:26.520
[Guest]: why Rahul Gandhi is not liked, India is now more democratic, less feudal at the level

01:20:26.520 --> 01:20:27.520
[Guest]: of how people think.

01:20:27.520 --> 01:20:33.080
[Guest]: I mean, I've said this often before, that why is MS Dhoni an icon?

01:20:33.080 --> 01:20:37.520
[Guest]: Because he's not Gavaskar, English speaking from Mumbai, why, you know, why is some young

01:20:37.520 --> 01:20:39.000
[Guest]: entrepreneur an icon?

01:20:39.000 --> 01:20:43.720
[Guest]: Because they're self made, you know, you know, sons of Ambani's and Bajaj's and Birla's.

01:20:43.720 --> 01:20:45.760
[Amit Varma]: So there is a journey going on.

01:20:45.760 --> 01:20:52.600
[Guest]: I mean, speak to the aspirational energies of economic growth, urbanization, you know,

01:20:52.600 --> 01:20:58.160
[Guest]: social media, the influence of the world is leading to a kind of in some ways, I mean,

01:20:58.160 --> 01:21:05.400
[Guest]: look at the transformation in my life, which is attitudes to sexuality, and gay rights.

01:21:05.400 --> 01:21:07.000
[Guest]: I mean, it's fantastic, right?

01:21:07.000 --> 01:21:08.000
[Guest]: You couldn't have thought of this.

01:21:08.000 --> 01:21:11.600
[Guest]: When I was young, I mean, homophobia was everywhere.

01:21:11.600 --> 01:21:12.600
[Guest]: That's not true.

01:21:12.600 --> 01:21:15.520
[Guest]: I mean, my mother thinks it's absolutely okay to be gay, right?

01:21:15.520 --> 01:21:17.600
[Guest]: I mean, she's 93, right?

01:21:17.600 --> 01:21:21.960
[Guest]: And this kind of thing is, she's not alone in this, people recognize that these are freedoms

01:21:21.960 --> 01:21:27.400
[Guest]: which people must enjoy, you know, so I think they are kind of, I mean, India's always moves

01:21:27.400 --> 01:21:32.760
[Guest]: in different, different places, even if the state is, wants to curb dissent and diversity,

01:21:32.760 --> 01:21:38.200
[Guest]: and individual freedoms, I think the world is changing in that direction.

01:21:38.200 --> 01:21:42.000
[Amit Varma]: I've taken a lot of your time, I'd initially let me inform my listeners, I'd initially

01:21:42.000 --> 01:21:45.800
[Amit Varma]: asked Ram for three hours of his time, because I thought we'll do a really nice leisurely

01:21:45.800 --> 01:21:50.160
[Amit Varma]: episode, but you you've been you've been traveling a lot, and you're a bit tired.

01:21:50.160 --> 01:21:55.000
[Amit Varma]: So we'll sort of wind it up at the 90 minute mark before we go sort of, you know, just

01:21:55.000 --> 01:21:58.160
[Amit Varma]: looking at India now, I mean, you're not just a person who's lived his whole life in India,

01:21:58.160 --> 01:22:02.920
[Amit Varma]: you have actually lived your significant part of your life in an India that goes before

01:22:02.920 --> 01:22:06.280
[Amit Varma]: all of this in your deep studies of history, and so on.

01:22:06.280 --> 01:22:12.120
[Amit Varma]: And you have sort of, in a sense, you're a prominent public intellectual, and in a sense,

01:22:12.120 --> 01:22:17.840
[Amit Varma]: you are out there in the public square as well today, you know, shaping the discourse.

01:22:17.840 --> 01:22:22.120
[Amit Varma]: Just looking at what's happening now, if I if I were to say that, what is your greatest

01:22:22.120 --> 01:22:25.800
[Amit Varma]: cause for fear of what could happen, say, by 2030?

01:22:25.800 --> 01:22:27.560
[Amit Varma]: And what is your greatest cause for hope?

01:22:27.560 --> 01:22:29.680
[Amit Varma]: What is the India you are afraid could happen?

01:22:29.680 --> 01:22:30.680
[Guest]: And what is the India that?

01:22:30.680 --> 01:22:35.080
[Guest]: No, I think, as I said, I'm more hopeful now than I've been for a long time.

01:22:35.080 --> 01:22:44.080
[Guest]: I think we have lost a lot of time and ground in the last 15 years to go back to what I

01:22:44.080 --> 01:22:45.080
[Guest]: said today.

01:22:45.080 --> 01:22:49.640
[Guest]: I think Manmohan Singh second term, and the two terms of Modi have set us back a great

01:22:49.640 --> 01:22:56.480
[Guest]: deal economically, institutionally, socially, morally, culturally, they've set us back.

01:22:56.480 --> 01:23:03.960
[Guest]: But three months ago, I may have thought to be going to descend into full fledged authoritarianism.

01:23:03.960 --> 01:23:04.960
[Guest]: That's not going to happen.

01:23:04.960 --> 01:23:07.120
[Guest]: I think the young have seen to that.

01:23:07.120 --> 01:23:11.320
[Guest]: And also what happened in Maharashtra has seen to that because a large state going out

01:23:11.320 --> 01:23:16.520
[Guest]: of the BJP state of that kind means federalism is a bulwark against full fledged authoritarianism

01:23:16.520 --> 01:23:17.520
[Guest]: of the right.

01:23:17.520 --> 01:23:20.020
[Guest]: Every half of India is outside the BJP.

01:23:20.020 --> 01:23:26.040
[Guest]: And even if four years later, the BJP reclaims MP in Rajasthan, even if they are reelected

01:23:26.040 --> 01:23:30.600
[Guest]: in UP, the south and the west and now increasing the east, you know, in the northeast, for

01:23:30.600 --> 01:23:32.520
[Guest]: example, is a great amount of discontent.

01:23:32.520 --> 01:23:39.120
[Guest]: So but I think this I'd say, if you take the medium term view, not the very long term view,

01:23:39.120 --> 01:23:47.840
[Guest]: I think Manmohan Singh, a big one, Narsimha Rao, Vajpayee and Manmohan Singh one, elevated

01:23:47.840 --> 01:23:48.840
[Guest]: India.

01:23:48.840 --> 01:23:56.400
[Guest]: You know, I've always been skeptical of India, but in different ways, despite their flaws,

01:23:56.400 --> 01:23:57.400
[Guest]: they were not perfect.

01:23:57.400 --> 01:24:02.300
[Guest]: For prime ministers, they made many flaws, but overall, the balance sheet was positive.

01:24:02.300 --> 01:24:09.680
[Guest]: That is, a country as large, as diverse, as complex as India, can progress only incrementally.

01:24:09.680 --> 01:24:13.560
[Guest]: You can't have a great revolution where you remove inequality, become a world power and

01:24:13.560 --> 01:24:16.120
[Guest]: you know, economic growth is 10% all the time.

01:24:16.120 --> 01:24:19.240
[Guest]: And there's no Hindu Muslim conflict, there's no caste atrocities.

01:24:19.240 --> 01:24:28.560
[Guest]: But Narsimha Rao, Vajpayee and Manmohan Singh, term one, took us to a level where I would

01:24:28.560 --> 01:24:38.120
[Guest]: say we were becoming a wealthier, a more secure, a safer, a more comfortable place to live

01:24:38.120 --> 01:24:39.120
[Guest]: in.

01:24:39.120 --> 01:24:40.120
[Guest]: Right.

01:24:40.120 --> 01:24:45.960
[Guest]: Manmohan Singh two, and the two terms of Modi have set us back.

01:24:45.960 --> 01:24:46.960
[Guest]: Quite a lot.

01:24:46.960 --> 01:24:47.960
[Guest]: Right.

01:24:47.960 --> 01:24:53.000
[Guest]: And so in that sense, we have lost quite substantially in the last 15 years, we would have by the

01:24:53.000 --> 01:24:55.440
[Guest]: time Modi completes the second term.

01:24:55.440 --> 01:25:02.400
[Guest]: But you know, if I'm allowed to, you know, quote myself, you know, in India after Gandhi,

01:25:02.400 --> 01:25:07.560
[Guest]: I kind of sort of said India is a 50-50 democracy, right?

01:25:07.560 --> 01:25:08.560
[Guest]: You remember that, right?

01:25:08.560 --> 01:25:09.560
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:25:09.560 --> 01:25:14.520
[Guest]: Now, last year, I said, after Kashmir, I said, we are 40-60, going towards 30-70.

01:25:14.520 --> 01:25:18.600
[Guest]: I think now we're up to 35 or 40%, right?

01:25:18.600 --> 01:25:25.280
[Guest]: So in that sense, we could have crossed the hump, those three prime ministers, Narsimha

01:25:25.280 --> 01:25:29.260
[Guest]: Rao, Vajpayee and Manmohan Singh, were leading us to cross the hump.

01:25:29.260 --> 01:25:32.400
[Guest]: And now we've gone back somewhere, you know, we're just muddling along in the middle as

01:25:32.400 --> 01:25:33.680
[Guest]: we have been.

01:25:33.680 --> 01:25:35.320
[Guest]: But the last few months have made me more hopeful.

01:25:35.320 --> 01:25:38.960
[Guest]: I mean, I don't think we are going into the abyss as I may have thought three or four

01:25:38.960 --> 01:25:39.960
[Guest]: months ago.

01:25:39.960 --> 01:25:43.800
[Guest]: It was very, very dark three or four months ago, the pall of fear is broken.

01:25:43.800 --> 01:25:48.160
[Guest]: I mean, if you look at the jokes about our ruling duo, I mean, they're delightful.

01:25:48.160 --> 01:25:53.200
[Guest]: I mean, you know, Modi met some students, he doesn't have, he won't meet the students

01:25:53.200 --> 01:25:58.320
[Guest]: protesting the seat, but he'll have these curated, specially curated meetings with students.

01:25:58.320 --> 01:26:00.720
[Guest]: And he was going to tell them all the exams.

01:26:00.720 --> 01:26:04.840
[Guest]: And this great cartoonist Satish Acharya had a cartoon which said, you know, if I fail,

01:26:04.840 --> 01:26:05.840
[Guest]: can I blame Pakistan?

01:26:05.840 --> 01:26:06.840
[Guest]: Lovely.

01:26:06.840 --> 01:26:08.840
[Guest]: So the pall of fear is broken.

01:26:08.840 --> 01:26:09.840
[Guest]: And I think that's great.

01:26:09.840 --> 01:26:13.760
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, that's one of the things that gives me hope, all the art and the humor.

01:26:13.760 --> 01:26:14.760
[Guest]: Absolutely, absolutely.

01:26:14.760 --> 01:26:20.440
[Guest]: I think there's a, I mean, there's a kind of book that will be written on the music,

01:26:20.440 --> 01:26:25.560
[Guest]: the poetry, the poems, the art, the cartoons, the graffiti, the slogans that have emerged

01:26:25.560 --> 01:26:26.560
[Guest]: from this movement.

01:26:26.560 --> 01:26:30.480
[Guest]: I'm sure there'll be, there's a great book, a young anthropologist will write about this.

01:26:30.480 --> 01:26:32.600
[Guest]: And I think these are very heartening signs.

01:26:32.600 --> 01:26:33.600
[Amit Varma]: Very inspiring words.

01:26:33.600 --> 01:26:35.360
[Amit Varma]: And people keep asking me for transcripts of the show.

01:26:35.360 --> 01:26:38.600
[Amit Varma]: And my reply to them now is hum kaagas nahi dikhayenge.

